WEBVTT

00:00:07.170 --> 00:00:08.980
PROFESSOR: Welcome back
to recitation.

00:00:08.980 --> 00:00:10.630
In this video segment
we're going to look

00:00:10.630 --> 00:00:12.020
at the chain rule.

00:00:12.020 --> 00:00:14.690
And specifically we're going to
answer a question that I've

00:00:14.690 --> 00:00:16.420
placed on the board.

00:00:16.420 --> 00:00:18.710
I want you to find two
values for theta.

00:00:18.710 --> 00:00:22.080
So that the d d theta of the
function cosine squared theta

00:00:22.080 --> 00:00:23.870
to the fourth equals 0.

00:00:23.870 --> 00:00:26.430
At this point I should also
point out a few things.

00:00:26.430 --> 00:00:30.080
One, theta is a variable
in this case.

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:33.230
And if you haven't seen it
before, frequently we use it

00:00:33.230 --> 00:00:35.470
when we're dealing with
trigonometric functions.

00:00:35.470 --> 00:00:39.490
Theta often represents the
variable that measures angle.

00:00:39.490 --> 00:00:42.130
So if you haven't seen
theta before, this is

00:00:42.130 --> 00:00:42.950
what it looks like.

00:00:42.950 --> 00:00:44.080
That's how you say it.

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:46.910
And I'm actually doing the same
things we've done before.

00:00:46.910 --> 00:00:50.140
I'm taking the derivative with
respect to the variable theta,

00:00:50.140 --> 00:00:52.690
of a function of theta.

00:00:52.690 --> 00:00:54.740
The other thing I want to point
out, which I think we

00:00:54.740 --> 00:00:57.880
know already, but just to be
sure, is it that this squared

00:00:57.880 --> 00:01:01.370
here, cosine squared theta to
the fourth, means I'm taking

00:01:01.370 --> 00:01:04.820
cosine of theta to the fourth
and I'm actually squaring it.

00:01:04.820 --> 00:01:08.870
So with that knowledge I would
like us to use the chain rule

00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:11.060
to find two values for
theta where this

00:01:11.060 --> 00:01:13.340
derivative is equal to 0.

00:01:13.340 --> 00:01:16.420
So I'll give you a moment to
take a stab at finding the

00:01:16.420 --> 00:01:19.620
derivative, setting it equal to
0 and finding some values

00:01:19.620 --> 00:01:23.750
for theta that make
this equation, the

00:01:23.750 --> 00:01:25.190
derivative equal 0.

00:01:25.190 --> 00:01:29.990
And we'll come back and then
I'll work it out as well.

00:01:29.990 --> 00:01:32.790
OK, so the first thing we
obviously need to do is be

00:01:32.790 --> 00:01:35.360
able to take the derivative
of this function on

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:36.360
the left-hand side.

00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:40.270
And I should say it's a little
more complicated than an

00:01:40.270 --> 00:01:41.960
example you saw in the lecture,
because in the

00:01:41.960 --> 00:01:43.570
lecture you were given
an example

00:01:43.570 --> 00:01:44.950
with just two functions.

00:01:44.950 --> 00:01:48.030
So I want to write it a little
differently just to show very

00:01:48.030 --> 00:01:50.830
obviously what the three
functions are we're composing.

00:01:50.830 --> 00:01:55.760
So this function I can rewrite
it as cosine theta to the

00:01:55.760 --> 00:01:57.010
fourth-- does that look like
a 4, there we go--

00:02:02.160 --> 00:02:04.600
and then I square that
whole thing.

00:02:04.600 --> 00:02:05.820
That's really what
the function is.

00:02:05.820 --> 00:02:07.040
OK?

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:10.690
So we can see what is the
outermost function here?

00:02:10.690 --> 00:02:14.170
The outermost function is
actually the quantity of

00:02:14.170 --> 00:02:15.150
something squared.

00:02:15.150 --> 00:02:17.660
So the outermost function
is x squared.

00:02:17.660 --> 00:02:20.520
What's the next function in,
in this composition?

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:23.450
The next function in is
the cosine function.

00:02:23.450 --> 00:02:26.790
And then the last function
in is the function taking

00:02:26.790 --> 00:02:28.570
something, raising
it to the fourth.

00:02:28.570 --> 00:02:31.090
So it's very important you
understand sort of the

00:02:31.090 --> 00:02:33.760
composition, which is the
outermost function, which is

00:02:33.760 --> 00:02:35.430
the innermost function?

00:02:35.430 --> 00:02:37.770
In order to do this
chain rule.

00:02:37.770 --> 00:02:47.750
Now as you saw in the
recitation, you were given the

00:02:47.750 --> 00:02:47.990
example, you had y as a function
of t-- sorry, not in

00:02:47.990 --> 00:02:49.570
recitation--

00:02:49.570 --> 00:02:50.220
in the lecture you were given,
you were given y as a function

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:53.090
of t or a function of x and then
you had to put one other

00:02:53.090 --> 00:02:54.330
variable in the middle.

00:02:54.330 --> 00:02:56.090
Here we're going to have a

00:02:56.090 --> 00:02:57.310
composition of three functions.

00:02:57.310 --> 00:03:00.650
So we need to have two other
things sort of in the middle.

00:03:00.650 --> 00:03:02.340
So let's write this out.

00:03:02.340 --> 00:03:06.130
First, the outermost function,
we'll call the whole thing y.

00:03:06.130 --> 00:03:11.440
So y is equal to x squared is
the outermost function.

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:14.690
So then this whole
thing is x now.

00:03:14.690 --> 00:03:19.305
So then we'll write x is
equal to cosine of w.

00:03:21.980 --> 00:03:27.602
And then w is equal to
theta to the fourth.

00:03:27.602 --> 00:03:28.600
OK.

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:33.440
Again this is what you saw
before in the lecture.

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:36.050
So you write the outermost
function.

00:03:36.050 --> 00:03:38.600
And then that function
is a function of

00:03:38.600 --> 00:03:40.590
cosine of another one.

00:03:40.590 --> 00:03:42.400
Cosine of w and w
is a function of

00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:42.920
theta to the fourth.

00:03:42.920 --> 00:03:45.990
So if I put all these back
together, I have theta to the

00:03:45.990 --> 00:03:49.830
fourth in here, and then I
square that, and I come back

00:03:49.830 --> 00:03:51.420
to the function I wanted.

00:03:51.420 --> 00:03:56.650
Now we know from the lecture
what we need to do to find,

00:03:56.650 --> 00:03:59.290
essentially, dy d theta.

00:03:59.290 --> 00:04:00.540
That's what we're looking for.

00:04:03.750 --> 00:04:08.380
So dy d theta, you'll see, you
remember from the lecture,

00:04:08.380 --> 00:04:18.500
should be dy dx times dx
dw times dw d theta.

00:04:18.500 --> 00:04:20.490
So it's slightly more
complicated than we saw before

00:04:20.490 --> 00:04:21.350
because there's one more term.

00:04:21.350 --> 00:04:22.970
OK.

00:04:22.970 --> 00:04:24.780
So now let's work out
what these are.

00:04:24.780 --> 00:04:27.820
Well dy dx is fairly
straightforward.

00:04:27.820 --> 00:04:29.900
dy dx is just 2x.

00:04:33.010 --> 00:04:35.330
And then dx dw, well what's
the derivative

00:04:35.330 --> 00:04:36.300
of the cosine function?

00:04:36.300 --> 00:04:39.090
The derivative of cosine
is negative sine.

00:04:39.090 --> 00:04:45.310
So this is times negative
sine of w times--

00:04:45.310 --> 00:04:47.330
and what's dw d theta?

00:04:47.330 --> 00:04:49.800
So w is the function theta
to the fourth.

00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:54.870
So dw d theta is 4 theta
to the third.

00:04:54.870 --> 00:04:59.570
Now when you look at this you
should remember, x we sort of

00:04:59.570 --> 00:05:02.510
inserted into the problem to
make the problem easier, and w

00:05:02.510 --> 00:05:04.730
we inserted into the problem to
make the problem easier for

00:05:04.730 --> 00:05:05.360
us to follow.

00:05:05.360 --> 00:05:07.520
So we don't want all
these x's and w's.

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:11.260
We want everything in terms
of, in terms of theta.

00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:12.390
But what is w?

00:05:12.390 --> 00:05:14.110
Well w is theta to the fourth.

00:05:14.110 --> 00:05:16.600
So I can replace that by
theta to the fourth.

00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:18.650
And what is x?

00:05:18.650 --> 00:05:20.590
x is cosine w.

00:05:20.590 --> 00:05:22.160
But w is theta to the fourth.

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:24.355
So x is actually cosine of
theta to the fourth.

00:05:24.355 --> 00:05:26.000
OK?

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:33.260
So I get 2 cosine of
theta to the fourth

00:05:33.260 --> 00:05:35.260
times negative sine--

00:05:35.260 --> 00:05:37.570
w again is theta
to the fourth--

00:05:37.570 --> 00:05:43.710
of theta to the fourth times
4 theta to the third.

00:05:43.710 --> 00:05:45.910
Let's make this nicer.

00:05:45.910 --> 00:05:48.100
I'll bring the coefficient and
the theta to the third in

00:05:48.100 --> 00:05:50.150
front and this minus
sign in front.

00:05:50.150 --> 00:05:55.850
I get negative 8 theta to the
third cosine of theta to

00:05:55.850 --> 00:06:00.340
fourth sine of theta
to the fourth.

00:06:00.340 --> 00:06:03.190
OK, and then the problem asks
to find where the derivative

00:06:03.190 --> 00:06:04.370
is equal to 0.

00:06:04.370 --> 00:06:05.640
Find two values.

00:06:05.640 --> 00:06:07.210
Now why did I ask you
to find two values?

00:06:07.210 --> 00:06:08.770
Because one is very easy.

00:06:08.770 --> 00:06:12.310
If this thing is set equal to 0,
one value should stand out

00:06:12.310 --> 00:06:15.750
right away for theta that
makes this product 0.

00:06:15.750 --> 00:06:17.840
And that is theta equals 0.

00:06:17.840 --> 00:06:20.320
So theta equals 0 is
our easiest answer.

00:06:26.690 --> 00:06:28.760
So if you didn't do that,
then you wanted the more

00:06:28.760 --> 00:06:30.810
challenging stuff, you
could have done the

00:06:30.810 --> 00:06:32.310
other things also.

00:06:32.310 --> 00:06:34.570
So what about cosine theta
to the fourth?

00:06:34.570 --> 00:06:37.830
If we want a product of three
things to be 0, then at least

00:06:37.830 --> 00:06:39.430
one of them has to be 0.

00:06:39.430 --> 00:06:41.660
So I could have set cosine
theta to the

00:06:41.660 --> 00:06:42.910
fourth equal to 0.

00:06:48.560 --> 00:06:51.170
And for what values of--

00:06:51.170 --> 00:06:54.230
an angle I should just say--
for what values of theta to

00:06:54.230 --> 00:06:56.340
the fourth is this
going to be zero?

00:06:56.340 --> 00:07:04.070
Well this means that theta to
the fourth is equal to either

00:07:04.070 --> 00:07:07.121
maybe pi over 2, or you
could add another pi.

00:07:07.121 --> 00:07:07.182
OK?

00:07:07.182 --> 00:07:11.690
So we could say, well let's just
say that's one example.

00:07:11.690 --> 00:07:14.830
Theta to the fourth equals pi
over 2 would work right?

00:07:14.830 --> 00:07:18.230
Because it cosine of pi
over 2 is equal to 0.

00:07:18.230 --> 00:07:20.200
OK?

00:07:20.200 --> 00:07:24.520
And so then we could have said
theta is equal to pi

00:07:24.520 --> 00:07:29.390
over 2 to the 1/4.

00:07:29.390 --> 00:07:31.470
That's another example there.

00:07:31.470 --> 00:07:34.900
We could have also done, we
could have added pi to this

00:07:34.900 --> 00:07:35.880
and gotten another answer.

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:37.360
But I only asked for two.

00:07:37.360 --> 00:07:40.320
So I guess that I'm allowed
to stop there.